        <h2 id="how-to-choose">How to choose a social media management tool</h2>
        <p>The right tool depends on your team size, platform mix, and primary use case. Use these criteria to narrow the field:</p>
        <ol>
          <li><strong>Platform coverage.</strong> Make sure the tool supports all the platforms you actively use. TikTok and Pinterest are not universally supported on lower-tier plans.</li>
          <li><strong>Account limits.</strong> How many social profiles can you connect? Some tools price per profile, others per user, others by plan tier. Calculate the real cost based on how many accounts you manage.</li>
          <li><strong>Inbox and engagement features.</strong> If managing community and responding to comments is a significant part of your workflow, prioritise tools with strong unified inbox features. If you just need scheduling, a simpler tool will do.</li>
          <li><strong>Reporting depth.</strong> If you need to present reports to clients or leadership, check whether the tool's reporting is robust enough — or whether you'll need a separate analytics tool anyway.</li>
          <li><strong>Team size and permissions.</strong> Solo users can use simple tools. Teams with multiple people, approval workflows, and role-based access need a tool built for collaboration.</li>
          <li><strong>Integration with other tools.</strong> Does it connect to your CRM, Google Analytics, Slack, or content management workflow? Integrations that reduce manual data transfer save significant operational overhead.</li>
        </ol>

        <h2 id="best-practices">How to get the most from a social media management tool</h2>
        <ol>
          <li><strong>Batch your content creation.</strong> Use the scheduling feature to its full potential by creating a week or two of content in a single session. Set aside a dedicated content creation block rather than creating and posting reactively.</li>
          <li><strong>Build an inbox management cadence.</strong> Define how often the inbox gets checked (twice daily is typical) and who is responsible. An inbox that's only reviewed once a week defeats the purpose of the unified inbox.</li>
          <li><strong>Use the analytics to run experiments.</strong> Post at different times, test different formats, try different caption lengths — and use the analytics dashboard to measure results. A management tool without an experimentation mindset is just a scheduler.</li>
          <li><strong>Set up content approval workflows before you need them.</strong> Establishing approval workflows before a crisis or a rushed campaign launch prevents the bottlenecks that come from ad-hoc approval via Slack DMs.</li>
          <li><strong>Audit your connected accounts quarterly.</strong> Disconnect platforms you're no longer active on, update access credentials, and remove team members who have left. Access hygiene is a security practice, not just a housekeeping one.</li>
          <li><strong>Customise for each platform.</strong> Don't publish identical content to all platforms. Use the tool's per-platform customisation to tailor captions, hashtags, and image crops to each platform's norms. The tool's purpose is efficiency — not homogenisation.</li>
        </ol>

        <div class="callout callout-warn">
          <div class="callout-label">A tool doesn't replace a strategy</div>
          <p>A social media management tool makes executing a social strategy more efficient. It doesn't create the strategy. Teams that invest in a tool without investing in content quality, audience understanding, and platform-specific knowledge will find they're producing and scheduling mediocre content more efficiently — which is not a competitive advantage. The tool amplifies the strategy; without a strategy, it amplifies noise.</p>
        </div>

